2026-02-27 08:55:28,651 2334379 DEBUG mcpp.tool CALL plan_task_notes_set args={'kind': 'goal', 'id': 438, 'text': 'Restructure the +input mixin (and all derived input mixins) to match DaisyUI v5\'s label-wrapper pattern. TWO deviations to fix:\n\n1. STRUCTURE: .input class is on the <input> element directly. DaisyUI v5 expects: <label class="input"><input/></label> — the label is the styled container, the input fills it. This enables icons, badges, suffix text inside the input visually.\n\n2. VALIDATION: Custom JS validatebox-plugin.js (ported from EasyUI) instead of HTML5 native validation + DaisyUI\'s CSS validator class. DaisyUI v5 uses <label class="input validator"> with HTML5 attributes (required, pattern, minlength, etc.) and .validator-hint for messages — all CSS-driven, no JS. Custom rules (inList, sqlsafe, csn) that have no HTML5 equivalent can use pattern attributes or a thin JS layer on top of the native Constraint Validation API.\n\nEvery input across 60+ pages is affected.\n\nCRITICAL RULES:\n- DO NOT touch any existing mixins (input.pug, form.pug, etc.) until the new pattern is proven\n- All development and prototyping MUST happen in the sandbox page: html/dui/mod/dev/sbox_input.pug (Development → Input Sandbox)\n- New mixin prototypes are defined locally in the sandbox page only\n- Existing mixins are only modified after the sandbox prototype is approved by the user'}
2026-02-27 08:56:55,029 2334379 DEBUG mcpp.tool CALL plan_task_notes_set args={'text': "Icons/badges inside label.input are purely visual — DaisyUI provides no built-in click handlers. But they are regular DOM elements, so we can wire up click events via standard JS. Mixin API could support e.g. icon: { name: 'search', click: 'openQbe' } with a data-action attribute for JS to hook into. This is how QBE search icon would trigger the QBE modal."}
